{
  "doc_id": "49340",
  "text": "Mucinous carcinoma, representing 1-3 % of breast cancers, has an average age at diagnosis of 70 [CITATION_1] , and is commonly estrogen receptor (ER)-positive and of low tumor grade [CITATION_2] ; survival is generally better than for ductal carcinoma [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Medullary carcinoma, representing 1-2 % of breast cancers, is more common among BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutation carriers, has an early age at onset, and is associated with hormone receptor negativity and high grade, but with similar or better survival compared with ductal carcinoma [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Tubular carcinoma, representing 1-2 % of breast cancers, is similar in age at diagnosis distribution to ductal carcinoma, but associated with small tumor size and better survival [16, 18-20, 23, 24] .",
